---
import CalculatorLayout from "../../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro";
import { AwsApiGatewayRequestEstimator as AwsApiGatewayRequestEstimatorComponent } from "../../components/calculators/AwsApiGatewayRequestEstimator";

const title = "API Gateway Request Volume Estimator";
const description =
  "Translate API Gateway traffic into monthly billable requests from baseline RPS, burst windows, and retry-heavy periods before you price transfer or downstream services.";
---
<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/calculators/aws-api-gateway-request-estimator"
  robots="noindex,follow"
  intro="Model monthly API Gateway request volume from baseline RPS, peak windows, and a retry multiplier so you can feed realistic numbers into cost estimates."
  examples={[
    "180 RPS baseline with a 10-hour peak window and 110% retry buffer.",
    "Mobile app traffic: 900 RPS baseline, 3,200 RPS peaks, and 120% multiplier.",
  ]}
  includes={[
    "Baseline requests from RPS, hours/day, and days/month.",
    "Peak window requests for launches, incidents, or campaigns.",
    "Retry multiplier to account for timeouts and bot traffic.",
  ]}
  excludes={[
    "Per-request pricing, transfer pricing, and access-log storage pricing.",
    "Caching, downstream service costs, and other non-request line items.",
  ]}
  how={[
    "Baseline requests = baseline RPS x baseline hours x 3600.",
    "Peak requests = peak RPS x peak hours x 3600.",
    "Total requests = (baseline + peak) x retry multiplier.",
  ]}
  faqs={[
    {
      q: "Should I include retries?",
      a: "Yes. Any retries that hit the gateway are billable and should be included in request volume.",
    },
    {
      q: "What counts as a peak window?",
      a: "Launches, batch processing, incident spikes, or seasonal traffic surges.",
    },
    {
      q: "Why not just use average RPS?",
      a: "Average hides spikes. Modeling a peak window improves accuracy and avoids under-budgeting.",
    },
  ]}
  lastUpdated="2026-01-30"
  related={[
    { href: "/calculators/aws-api-gateway-cost-calculator", label: "AWS API Gateway cost calculator" },
    { href: "/guides/aws-api-gateway-estimate-requests", label: "Guide: estimate API requests" },
    { href: "/guides/aws-api-gateway-pricing", label: "Guide: API Gateway pricing" },
  ]}
>
  <AwsApiGatewayRequestEstimatorComponent client:load />

  <div class="prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:0">
      This calculator is the request-volume workflow of the API Gateway cluster: it exists to turn RPS, peak windows,
      retries, bots, and automation into defendable billable requests before pricing starts.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      It does not price transfer, request fees, or access-log storage; once the request model is stable, hand the
      result to the main API Gateway cost calculator or the pricing guide.
    </p>

    <h2 style="margin-top:0">API Gateway request volume is mostly a traffic-shape and retry-amplification problem</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      This estimator is for translating API traffic behavior into billable gateway requests. The biggest misses usually
      come from retry storms, bot traffic, mobile reconnect behavior, or burst windows that are small in duration but
      large enough to move the monthly bill.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Baseline flow</strong>: the ordinary request path that runs most of the month.</li>
      <li><strong>Burst windows</strong>: launches, campaigns, cron workloads, or incident traffic that distort averages.</li>
      <li><strong>Amplifiers</strong>: retries, bots, automation, and client behavior that create billable requests without adding business value.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Where API Gateway estimates usually drift</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Average RPS looks safe, but short burst windows materially change monthly request totals.</li>
      <li>Only successful application traffic is counted while retries and failed gateway requests are ignored.</li>
      <li>Bot and automation traffic is treated as noise even though it still hits the gateway and gets billed.</li>
      <li>Peak traffic is modeled, but its duration is guessed too low.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What to review before feeding this into the main API Gateway calculator</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Use gateway-side or edge-side counts that include all billable requests, not only successful application responses.</li>
      <li>Model peak windows explicitly instead of hiding them in one monthly average.</li>
      <li>Keep retries and bot traffic visible so the estimate can be defended in review.</li>
      <li>Treat this page as a request-volume estimator only, not as a full API cost model.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What this calculator should hand off next</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Hand off to <a href="/calculators/aws-api-gateway-cost-calculator/">AWS API Gateway cost calculator</a> when request volume is stable enough to convert into request-fee and transfer spend.</li>
      <li>Hand off to <a href="/guides/aws-api-gateway-pricing/">API Gateway pricing</a> if request measurement changes what belongs inside the API Gateway bill versus adjacent transfer or logging cost.</li>
      <li>Do not use this page as a shortcut for logging-side cost work; <a href="/calculators/aws-api-gateway-access-log-cost-calculator/">API Gateway access log cost calculator</a> is the page for ingestion and retention modeling.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:0">
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/aws-api-gateway-cost-calculator/">AWS API Gateway cost calculator</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-api-gateway-estimate-requests/">Guide: estimate API requests</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</CalculatorLayout>
